{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:25:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:25:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18150"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18150"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.13,0.39,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10864"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7328"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ulnar tunnel, also known as Guyon\u0027s canal, is an anatomical passageway in the wrist that allows the ulnar nerve and artery to enter the hand. It is important in the context of ulnar nerve compression syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures forms a boundary of the ulnar tunnel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pisohamate ligament","Palmar radiocarpal ligament","Superficial transverse metacarpal ligament","Radial collateral ligament","Dorsal radiocarpal ligament"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is the \u003Cstrong\u003Episohamate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, which forms the roof of the ulnar tunnel along with the transverse carpal ligament. The ulnar tunnel is a fibro-osseous canal located on the ulnar side of the wrist, and it is important for the passage of the ulnar nerve and artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalmar radiocarpal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located on the palmar side of the wrist but does not form a boundary of the ulnar tunnel.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial transverse metacarpal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located in the palm and is not related to the ulnar tunnel.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located on the radial side of the wrist and does not form a boundary of the ulnar tunnel.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal radiocarpal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located on the dorsal side of the wrist and is not involved in forming the ulnar tunnel.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ulnar tunnel, also known as Guyon\u0027s canal, is bounded by the transverse carpal ligament and the pisohamate ligament.","The ulnar tunnel allows passage of the ulnar nerve and artery into the hand.","Understanding the anatomy of the ulnar tunnel is important for diagnosing ulnar nerve compression."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18150"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T01:08:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T01:09:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10864"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{